{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GCT2iVLCD1TPRxo2PcJjSV","type":"tool_result","content":"23-\n24-## Executive Summary\n25-\n26:codeharness is an npm CLI and Claude Code plugin that orchestrates autonomous coding agents across multiple frameworks — Claude Code, OpenAI Codex, OpenCode (with omo), and gstack — through a single workflow engine. Today, each coding agent framework is a silo: you pick one and live with its strengths and blind spots. codeharness breaks that lock-in by letting you define workflows where each task dispatches to the best framework and model for the job.\n27-\n28-The critical use case is **cross-framework verification**: develop a feature in Claude Code with Opus, then verify it in Codex with a completely independent agent runtime. The verifier literally cannot cheat — it's a different binary, different model, different context. This architectural separation of concerns delivers trust that same-framework self-verification cannot.\n29-\n30-The workflow engine already exists (`tasks → flow` YAML with loop blocks). This PRD extends it with per-task `driver` and `model` fields, a driver abstraction that wraps each framework's CLI, and a live TUI workflow visualization showing the current position in the execution graph.\n31-\n32:Two problems this solves. First, **framework lock-in** — teams pick Claude Code or Codex and miss capabilities the other offers. codeharness makes them composable. Second, **invisible orchestration** — when an autonomous loop runs for hours, you can't tell where it is or what framework is executing. The TUI workflow map makes the multi-framework pipeline visible and legible in real time.\n33-\n34-### What Makes This Special\n35-\n36-- **Cross-framework verification by architecture** — dev and verify tasks run on different agent runtimes. Independence is structural, not policy. The verifier has no access to the developer's context, tools, or session.\n37-- **Mix-and-match orchestration** — each workflow task specifies its own driver (claude-code, codex, opencode) and model. Use Opus for complex architecture, Sonnet for routine implementation, Codex for cost-effective batch verification.\n38:- **Plugin ecosystem integration** — gstack skills run inside Claude Code sessions, omo agents run inside OpenCode sessions. codeharness orchestrates at the framework level; plugins orchestrate within each framework.\n39-- **Live workflow visualization** — the existing Ink TUI gains a schematic workflow graph (`implement → verify → loop[retry, verify]`) with highlighted current position, framework label per task, and cost/time per node.\n40-- **CLI-wrapping driver model** — all target frameworks (Claude Code Agent SDK, `codex` CLI, `opencode` CLI) are wrapped uniformly. No framework exposes a programmatic SDK for external orchestration — codeharness fills that gap by wrapping their CLIs and parsing their outputs.\n41-\n--\n58-\n59-### Business Success\n60-\n61:- **3-month goal:** All three drivers (Claude Code, Codex, OpenCode) working end-to-end with cross-framework verification producing proof documents. gstack and omo integration functional via parent drivers.\n62-- **6-month goal:** Stable multi-framework workflows in production use. Community contributors can add new drivers.\n63-- **Positioning:** codeharness is the only tool that orchestrates across coding agent frameworks. No competitor does cross-framework dispatch with workflow visualization.\n64-- **Dogfooding:** codeharness development itself uses cross-framework verification — dev in Claude Code, verify in Codex.\n--\n96-\n97-**Core User Journeys Supported:**\n98-- Journey 1 (Sasha — Cross-Framework Verify): full workflow config → run → cross-framework verification\n99:- Journey 2 (Autonomous Loop — Multi-Framework): all three frameworks in a single sprint\n100-- Journey 3 (Sasha — TUI Watching): workflow graph visible during execution\n101-\n102-**Must-Have Capabilities:**\n--\n114-| Loop iteration counter | TUI shows loop count on loop blocks |\n115-| Output contract passing | Serialize task output to JSON, feed as input to next task across framework boundary |\n116-| Backward compatibility | Workflows without `driver` field default to `claude-code` |\n117:| gstack integration | gstack skills loaded into claude-code driver sessions via config |\n118:| omo integration | omo agents loaded into opencode driver sessions via config |\n119-| Driver capability matrix | Docs showing what each driver can/cannot do |\n120-| Cost-based routing hints | Suggest cheaper driver for simple tasks |\n121-\n--\n138-| OpenCode CLI output format differs from expected | Driver parsing fails | Start with simplest output mode, iterate on real output |\n139-| Cross-framework context passing loses information | Verification gets incomplete picture | Output contracts are explicit JSON — test with round-trip validation |\n140-| Driver spawn latency too high | UX degradation | Profile first, optimize later. 3s target is generous for CLI cold start |\n141:| Codex/OpenCode CLI auth model incompatible with headless use | Can't run in autonomous loop | Test headless auth early. Fall back to whichever driver works first |\n142-| Framework CLIs have different permission/sandbox models | Tasks fail on one driver but not another | Driver capability matrix — document what each driver can/cannot do, fail fast with clear error |\n143-\n144-**Market Risks:**\n--\n184-\n185----\n186-\n187:### Journey 2: The Autonomous Loop — Multi-Framework Sprint Execution\n188-\n189-The codeharness engine picks up a 6-story sprint. The workflow is configured with Claude Code for implementation, OpenCode for code review, and Codex for verification.\n190-\n--\n250-| Journey | Capabilities Revealed |\n251-|---------|----------------------|\n252-| **Sasha — Cross-Framework Verify** | Per-task driver/model in workflow YAML, driver abstraction, cross-framework output contract passing, TUI workflow graph with framework labels |\n253:| **Autonomous Loop — Multi-Framework** | Driver factory, CLI spawning for each framework, stream event normalization across drivers, TUI multi-framework rendering, cost tracking per driver |\n254-| **Sasha — TUI Watching** | Persistent workflow graph in TUI, current position highlighting, per-node cost/time, loop iteration counter, framework label per task node |\n255-| **Marcus — New Driver** | `AgentDriver` interface, driver registration, CLI wrapping pattern, stream output parsing, <300 LOC per driver |\n256-\n--\n279-- **Claude Code** — Agent SDK for programmatic dispatch, but only to Claude models. No multi-framework.\n280-- **OpenCode** — Supports 75+ models but within a single framework. No cross-framework orchestration.\n281-- **Codex CLI** — OpenAI models only, no SDK for external dispatch.\n282:- **gstack** — Claude Code plugin with role-based skills. Not an orchestrator.\n283:- **omo** — OpenCode plugin with multi-agent support. Framework-internal only.\n284-- **No tool** combines cross-framework dispatch, workflow DAG execution, and live TUI visualization.\n285-\n286-### Validation Approach\n--\n328-| claude-code | Agent SDK (in-process) | StreamEvent (native) | Anthropic API key |\n329-| codex | `codex` CLI | stdout NDJSON | OpenAI API key / ChatGPT account |\n330-| opencode | `opencode` CLI | stdout | Per-provider keys |\n331:| gstack | via claude-code driver | StreamEvent (native) | Anthropic API key |\n332:| omo | via opencode driver | stdout | Per-provider keys |\n333-\n334:**Note:** gstack and omo are plugins within their respective frameworks — they don't need separate drivers. gstack skills activate inside Claude Code sessions (claude-code driver), omo agents activate inside OpenCode sessions (opencode driver). The workflow configures which plugins/skills load, not a separate driver.\n335-\n336-### Installation & Distribution\n337-\n--\n396-\n397-### Plugin Ecosystem Integration\n398-\n399:- FR21: User can configure gstack skills to load within claude-code driver sessions via workflow or agent config\n400:- FR22: User can configure omo agents to load within opencode driver sessions via workflow or agent config\n401:- FR23: System can pass plugin-specific configuration to the driver's CLI invocation (e.g., `--plugin`, `--agent` flags)\n402-\n403-### TUI Workflow Visualization\n404-\n--\n452-- NFR9: Claude Code driver must maintain compatibility with Agent SDK `@anthropic-ai/claude-agent-sdk` pinned version\n453-- NFR10: Output contract JSON format must be stable across driver versions — contracts written by one driver must be readable by any other\n454-- NFR11: Workflow YAML schema changes must be backward compatible — old workflows work without modification\n455:- NFR12: Plugin ecosystem integration (gstack, omo) must not require modifications to the plugins themselves — configuration only\n456-\n457-### Reliability\n458-"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01MERTQEVoM1FQ7mMnPAJnfv","session_id":"49777568-67d3-419d-b985-1c272283fc99","uuid":"34bd647d-8a5f-4868-95d5-c2620a9880e6","timestamp":"2026-04-03T12:25:16.070Z"}
